4.3.1. BCC vs. CCR
Both the BCC and CCR models were conceived within the Management
Science tradition. In some applications of these models, this involvement
permits the incorporation of management judgments into the analysis.
Furthermore, the inherent complexity of real-world decision-making often
introduces a degree of randomness or deviation from normality in the
34
characteristics under consideration, which can partly stem from the unique
nature of the data involved in these applications (Olesen & Petersen, 2016).
The BCC was developed as an extension of the CCR and provides a more
flexible approach to efficiency analysis. In the BCC, DMUs are evaluated based
on their ability to produce multiple outputs with multiple inputs while
considering VRS. One of the primary distinctions is the consideration of VRS in
the BCC, allowing for a more realistic assessment of efficiency. While the CCR
model assumes CRS, the BCC allows for the identification of increasing or
decreasing returns to scale, offering a more accurate representation of DMU
performance. These advancements make the BCC a more robust tool for
analyzing efficiency, which is why it will be the method used to develop our
model.
